  "prompt": "What is the salary of various elected representatives in India?",
  "response": "The salaries of elected representatives in India vary based on their positions, states, and any additional allowances they may receive. Here is a general overview:\n\n1. **Members of Parliament (MPs):**\n   - **Lok Sabha (Lower House) MPs:**\n     - Basic Salary: \u20b91,00,000 per month\n     - Constituency Allowance: \u20b970,000 per month\n     - Office Expense Allowance: \u20b960,000 per month\n     \n   - **Rajya Sabha (Upper House) MPs:**\n     - Basic Salary: \u20b91,00,000 per month\n     - Constituency Allowance: \u20b970,000 per month\n     - Office Expense Allowance: \u20b960,000 per month\n     \n2. **Prime Minister of India:**\n   - Basic Salary: \u20b92,00,000 per month\n   - Other allowances, including residential expenses, travel, and security.\n\n3. **President of India:**\n   - Salary: \u20b95,00,000 per month\n   \n4. **Chief Ministers and Legislative Assembly Members:**\n   - **Chief Ministers:**\n     - Salary varies by state. Generally, it ranges from \u20b950,000 to \u20b93,00,000 per month, with additional perks and allowances.\n     \n   - **Members of Legislative Assembly (MLAs):**\n     - Salaries also vary greatly by state. For instance, MLAs in states like Delhi and Maharashtra may receive around \u20b92,50,000 per month including allowances, while those in smaller or less affluent states may receive significantly less.\n\n5. **Governors of States:**\n   - Salary: \u20b93,50,000 per month\n   \nThese figures can change based on amendments, policies, and state-specific regulations. Elected representatives often receive additional benefits and perks, including accommodation, travel allowances, and pensions, which significantly add to their overall compensation packages.",
